The '''yellow-bellied flycatcher''' ('''''Empidonax flaviventris''''') is a small insect-eating bird of the [[tyrant flycatcher]] family.

== Description ==
Adults have greenish upperparts and yellowish underparts (especially on the throat), with a dusky wash on the chest. They have a white or yellow eye ring that lacks the teardrop projection of the [[Empidonax difficilis|western flycatcher]], white or yellowish wing bars that contrast strongly against the black wings, a broad, flat bill, and a relatively short tail when compared to other members of the genus. The upper mandible of the bill is dark, while the lower mandible is orange-pink. DNA testing in 2014 confirmed a field mark, involving the extent of buffy edging on the secondaries, to reliably distinguish this species from the western flycatcher.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Engel |first1=Joshua |title=A first for Illinois, discovered in The Field Museum's collection |url=https://www.fieldmuseum.org/blog/first-illinois-discovered-field-museums-collection |publisher=Field Museum of Natural History |access-date=19 February 2022 |date=26 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Engel |first1=Joshua |title=Follow up: A first for Illinois, discovered in the Field Museum's collection |url=https://www.fieldmuseum.org/blog/follow-first-illinois-discovered-field-museums-collection |publisher=Field Museum of Natural History |access-date=19 February 2022 |date=2 December 2014}}</ref>

'''Measurements''':<ref>{{Cite web|title=Yellow-bellied Flycatcher Identification, All About Birds, Cornell Lab of Ornithology|url=https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher/id|access-date=2020-09-27|website=www.allaboutbirds.org|language=en}}</ref>

* '''Length''': {{convert|5.1|-|5.9|in|cm|abbr=on}}
* '''Weight''': {{convert|0.3|-|0.6|oz|g|abbr=on}}
* '''Wingspan''': {{convert|7.1|-|7.9|in|cm|abbr=on}}

Yellow-bellied flycatchers wait on a perch low or in the middle of a tree and fly out to catch insects in flight, sometimes hovering over foliage. They sometimes eat berries or seeds.

[[File:Empidonax flaviventris - Yellow-bellied Flycatcher XC134691.ogg|thumb|Yellow-bellied flycatcher song, recorded in Minnesota in late May]]

The yellow-bellied flycatcher's song can be transcribed as a rough, descending "''tse''-berk", which can be similar to the more common [[Empidonax minimus|least flycatcher's]] snappier, more evenly pitched "che-bek."
[[File:Yellow-bellied Flycatcher2.jpg|thumb|right| Yellow-bellied Flycatcher at Rancho Naturalista Baja - Costa Rica]]
== Breeding ==
Their breeding habitat is wet northern woods, especially spruce bogs, across Canada and the northeastern United States. They make a cup nest in [[sphagnum]] moss on or near the ground.

== Migration ==
These birds [[bird migration|migrate]] to southern Mexico and Central America.

